<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//thelede.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/02/live-video-from-senate-hearing-on-g-m-defects/" data-title="Highlights from Senate Hearing on G.M. Defects" data-description="Highlights from the Senate hearing in Washington, where Mary T. Barra, chief executive officer of General Motors, was questioned by lawmakers about ignition defects that led to a massive recall and are linked to 13 deaths.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mary T. Barra, the chief executive of General Motors, faced tough questions during a Senate hearing Wednesday about the company&#8217;s failure to address safety issues, as our colleagues, Bill Vlasic and Matthew L. Wald <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/04/03/business/gm-chief-opens-testimony-to-senate-panel.html">report.</a> </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">David Friedman, the acting head of the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, also testified at the Senate hearing and surprised lawmakers by admitting he did not know his agency had subpoena power to demand documents. The committee is investigating why it took more than a decade for G.M. and the nation&#8217;s auto regulatory agency to address a defect that has been linked to 13 deaths and prompted a recall of 2.6 million cars. Highlights from the hearing were contributed by Mr. Wald and other New York Times reporters, including Rebecca R. Ruiz and Danielle Ivory.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="more-236294"></span>
<div id="liveUpdatesModule" class="liveUpdatesModule">
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="top-auto-regulator-didnt-know-he-had-subpoena-power" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#top-auto-regulator-didnt-know-he-had-subpoena-power">2:05 P.M.</a></span> <strong>Top Auto Regulator Didn&#8217;t Know He Had Subpoena Power</strong></h5>
</p></div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In an exchange with lawmakers, Mr. Friedman acknowledged that he did not know his agency had the ability to use subpoena power to demand documents from automakers. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Friedman told the Senate subcommittee that the N.H.T.S.A. had been paying close attention to legal action related to potential car safety defects.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Senator McCaskill asked Mr. Friedman if his agency had legal standing to demand from automakers the details of sealed and confidential lawsuits and legal settlements that could be connected to safety defects.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He said he did not think the agency had that ability.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Then she asked Mr. Friedman if the safety regulatory agency had subpoena power to request such documents. âYou can subpoena, right?â she asked.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Friedman checked with his staff, sitting behind him, and said yes.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIt worries me that you did not know,â the senator said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIt worries me as well,â Mr. Friedman said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Senator McCaskill asked how often the safety regulators had used subpoena power to get such records. Mr. Friedman said he would check and get back to the panel.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>DANIELLE IVORY</em></p>
</div></div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="audit-under-way-of-auto-regulatory-agency" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#audit-under-way-of-auto-regulatory-agency">1:21 P.M.</a></span> <strong>Audit Under Way of Auto Regulatory Agency</strong></h5>
</p></div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The senators also heard from the Transportation Departmentâs inspector general, Calvin L. Scovel III, who was asked by the department&#8217;s secretary to audit N.H.T.S.A.âs performance.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Like Ms. Barra, Mr. Scovel noted that a fuller investigation was continuing. He said that partly in response to an earlier audit by his office, the highway agency had put new procedures into place after the problem with Toyotas and unintended acceleration. âWe donât know how effective these new processes will be,ââ he said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>MATTHEW L. WALD</em></p>
</div></div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="top-auto-regulator-still-puzzled-over-air-bags" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#top-auto-regulator-still-puzzled-over-air-bags">1:20 P.M.</a></span> <strong>Top Auto Regulator Still Puzzled Over Airbags</strong></h5>
</p></div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">After grilling Ms. Barra, members of the Senate subcommittee were easier on David J. Friedman, the acting director of the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration.  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Friedman, who came to the agency from<a href=" //www.sae.org/congress/friedman.htm"> an environmental group where he specialized </a>in fuel economy and alternative fuels,  said that his agency was still struggling to understand the connection between faulty ignition switches and the failure of the airbags to deploy. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âTo be honest, it doesnât make sense to me,â he said. Agency officials have said that turning off the ignition somehow altered the control algorithm used by the airbag system to decide when to deploy; the airbags themselves are designed to work even if the electrical system is not functioning.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And agency investigators were initially led astray by the circumstances of one crash in which a car made a relatively soft impact with trees, and the driver was not belted. Airbags are designed to not deploy when the driver is not belted and the impact is less severe, Mr. Friedman said, because in that circumstance, the airbag could do more harm than good.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">One issue clearly within the purview of Congress is the governmentâs ability to see court documents that are sealed as a result of settlements between an automaker and the family of a person killed in a car alleged to be defective. As in the Ford-Firestone suits in the 1990s, lawmakers expressed concern that G.M. has settled suits secretly in Chevy Cobalt cases. Ms. Barra declined to say.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>MATTHEW L. WALD</em></p>
</div></div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="victims-family-questions-how-g-m-chief-couldnt-know" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#victims-family-questions-how-g-m-chief-couldnt-know">12:33 P.M.</a></span> <strong>Victim&#8217;s Family Questions How G.M. Chief Couldn&#8217;t Know </strong></h5>
</p></div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Gordon Hair, whose only child died in an accident in December 2009, has been watching parts of the hearings from Stony Point, Va.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIâm never horribly impressed with these Senate inquiries because they donât really ask very many questions,â he said. âAnd they accept it when she says itâs an ongoing investigation.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Hairâs son, Benjamin, a 20-year-old pharmacy student, died while driving home on a Sunday morning in a Pontiac G5. His airbags did not go off.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Hairs have received dozens of letters about issues with their sonâs car since his crash.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âDonât tell me the corporation itself didnât know,â Mr. Hair said. âI realize the C.E.O. needs to protect the assets of the company, but there needs to be no investigation. Theyâre paying to do an investigation in their own house, and they already know what happened.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Hair brought up Ms. Barraâs background in product development. âIâm not buying what sheâs trying to sell,â he said. âShe was basically in charge of parts at one point. I think she may be protecting herself.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He was frustrated at the unproductive answers Ms. Barra delivered. &#8220;Sheâs not doing anything except stonewalling and saying sheâs a mother and has children and is sorry and is communicating with the families.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Hair also reacted strongly to the low cost of repairing a faulty ignition switch  &#8212; a couple dollars &#8212; that several Senators had mentioned.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThat cost wasnât the reason they didnât do the recall,â Mr. Hair said, pointing to the company&#8217;s bankruptcy filing and public relations management. âIt was because it would affect their sales of new cars. Their financial standing at that time in 2009, many months before my son was killed, that might have been a reason for not recalling.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He said he did not believe the total death count was limited to what G.M. has reported. âIf there are only 13 people who died, donât you think someone could have called them to say theyâre sorry? Thatâs only 13 calls.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>REBECCA R. RUIZ</em></p>
</div></div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="lawmakers-ask-about-lawsuits-brought-against-g-m" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#lawmakers-ask-about-lawsuits-brought-against-g-m">12:26 P.M.</a></span> <strong>Lawmakers Ask About Lawsuits Brought Against G.M.</strong></h5>
</p></div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Senator McCaskill asked Ms. Barra to provide figures on how many lawsuits related to the ignition switch issue had been filed against G.M., how many had been settled, and how many had terms of confidentiality attached.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âHow much whack-a-mole has been going on?â the senator asked.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Several lawsuits about the safety defect have been identified, but there may be many more. Arguably the best-known case is a suit that was brought by the family of Jennifer Brooke Melton, 29, who lost control of her 2005 Cobalt on a Georgia highway in March 2010 when the key moved to the accessory position, shutting down power and air bags. (The accessory position turns off the car, but allows certain electronics, like the radio, to run.) The case was settled on Sept. 13 and the terms were confidential.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">G.M. had previously settled a lawsuit brought by the family of Hasaya Chansuthus, 25, who crashed her 2006 Cobalt in Murfreesboro, Tenn., even though Ms. Chansuthusâs blood-alcohol level was more than twice the legal limit. Data from the black box showed that the key was in the accessory or off position, according to court records, and the air bags did not deploy. The terms of that settlement are also confidential.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>DANIELLE IVORY</em></p>
</div></div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="no-g-m-employees-have-been-fired-resulting-from-defect" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#no-g-m-employees-have-been-fired-resulting-from-defect">12:17 P.M.</a></span> <strong>No G.M. Employees Have Been Fired Resulting from Defect</strong></h5>
</p></div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When asked if any G.M. employees have been terminated as a result of the failure to identify and warn about the defect over the last 10 years, Ms. Barra said that she was waiting for an internal investigation to be completed before making any personnel actions. She said that &#8220;appropriate action&#8221; would be taken at that time. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">She said that no G. M. employees have been fired for actions related to the defect and the recall. </p>
</div></div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="lawmakers-ask-barra-how-she-didnt-know-about-defect" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#lawmakers-ask-barra-how-she-didnt-know-about-defect">12:06 P.M.</a></span> <strong>Lawmakers Ask Barra How She Didn&#8217;t Know About Defect</strong></h5>
</p></div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/02/us/ledebarra/ledebarra-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/02/us/ledebarra/ledebarra-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/02/us/ledebarra/ledebarra-blog480.jpg" id="100000002802488" width="480" height="326" alt="General Motorsâ chief executive, Mary T. Barra, testified before a Senate committee on Wednesday."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="326"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">General Motorsâ chief executive, Mary T. Barra, testified before a Senate committee on Wednesday.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Pablo Martinez Monsivais/Associated Press</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ms. Barra completed her testimony during the House hearing Tuesday without much effort by the lawmakers to tie her personally to the various actions at the company that allowed the bad switches to persist for a decade. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Not so in the Senate on Wednesday. The subcommittee chairwoman, Claire McCaskill, a Democrat from Missouri, grilled her on what happened after a G.M. engineer testified under oath that he knew nothing about a part change, but he had signed off on the change. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ms. Barra said she had ordered more communication between the lawyers and the engineers. Yes, said Ms. McCaskill, but what about communications among the lawyers? What was done when an apparent perjury become obvious?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ms. Barra said she did not know yet.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThat is incredibly frustrating to me, that you wouldnât have a simple timeline of what happened,ââ Ms. McCaskill said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Barbara Boxer, Democrat of California, ran through Ms. Barraâs 33-year resume at GM and asked why she had never heard of the switch problem in any of her previous roles. Ms. Boxer also referred back to the case of the Ford Pinto, which had a gasoline tank that was prone to explode when the car was struck from the rear. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ford documents showed that the company decided it would be less expensive to pay settlements in death and injury cases than to fix the part at a cost of $11 per vehicle, Senator Boxer said.  And she said that G.M. was still making safety decisions based on costs.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ms. Barra said that had changed. &#8220;If itâs a safety issue there should not be a business case calculated,ââ she said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>MATTHEW L. WALD</em></p>
</div></div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="barra-says-she-would-allow-her-son-to-drive-a-cobalt" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#barra-says-she-would-allow-her-son-to-drive-a-cobalt">11:43 A.M.</a></span> <strong>Barra Says She Would Allow Her Son to Drive a Cobalt</strong></h5>
</p></div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Senator Richard Blumenthal, a Democrat from Connecticut, sharply questioned Ms. Barra about whether she should be telling people that Cobalts are safe to drive as long as they remove extra items on their key chains.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Holding up a poster board imprinted with the ignition-switch recall notice, he read aloud: âIt says the risk increases if your key chain is carrying added weight â¦or your vehicle experiences rough road conditions or other jarring or impact-related events.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Blumenthal asked Ms. Barra if she would allow her children to drive a Cobalt.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI would allow my sonâ to drive a Cobalt, Ms. Barra said, âif he had only the ignition key.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Challenging Ms. Barraâs assertion that Cobalts are safe to drive when using one unattached key in the ignition, Mr. Blumenthal asked about the risk because of bumpy roads.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ms. Barra dismissed that concern, citing test-drives the company had conducted in various road conditions. &#8220;The testing that we have done is that the weight would not cause that issue,&#8221; she said.  &#8220;If someone is uncomfortable, we are providing loaners. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI would respectfully advise you ask your customers to get loaners,â Mr. Blumenthal said, concluding his remarks.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>REBECCA R. RUIZ</em></p>
</div></div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="barra-says-she-may-not-share-findings-of-internal-probe" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#barra-says-she-may-not-share-findings-of-internal-probe">11:25 A.M.</a></span> <strong>Barra Says She May Not Share Internal Inquiry Findings</strong></h5>
</p></div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Under questioning about the company&#8217;s internal investigation, Ms. Barra once again said that G.M. may not share findings of the companyâs internal investigation âif there is an issue of competitiveness.â She clarified that anything related to the safety issue at hand or a broader safety issue would be shared with regulators, lawmakers and the public.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">During Tuesday&#8217;s House hearing, Ms. Barra had <a href="//thelede.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/01/live-updates-from-house-hearing-on-g-m-defects/?">a lengthy back-and-forth </a>with Representative Paul Tonko, in which Ms. Barra said she would commit only to sharing &#8220;appropriate&#8221; information.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>DANIELLE IVORY</em></p>
</div></div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="g-m-customers-facing-problems-getting-loaner-cars" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#g-m-customers-facing-problems-getting-loaner-cars">11:16 A.M.</a></span> <strong>G.M. Customers Facing Problems Getting Loaner Cars</strong></h5>
</p></div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ms. Barra said that G.M. was offering loaner cars at no cost to drivers of the recalled cars and has already loaned out 13,000 vehicles.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But G.M. has faced problems in providing rental cars to customers. In its instructions to dealers, the automaker said that while it usually requires that those rentals be G.M. vehicles, other makes were acceptable because so many would be needed. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Also, many Chevrolet Cobalt and Saturn Ion drivers are younger than 25 and are generally too young to rent cars or are subject to high rental surcharges. G.M. has told dealers that a guardian could sign the rental contract.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">According to the American Car Rental Association, a trade group, there were 1.95 million vehicles available for rent in 2013. G.M. has recalled 2.6 million cars linked to the ignition defect.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>DANIELLE IVORY</em></p>
</div></div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="victims-mother-wonders-why-g-m-withheld-information" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#victims-mother-wonders-why-g-m-withheld-information">11:09 A.M.</a></span> <strong>Victim&#8217;s Mother Wonders Why G.M. Withheld Information</strong></h5>
</p></div>
<div class="updated-entry-content">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">From her home in New Bethlehem, Pa., Melanie Raybuck is following the hearing closely and wondering why it has taken so long for an explanation about a defect in the car her daughter was driving when she died. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ms. Raybuckâs daughter, Kelley, was killed a week before Christmas, in December 2009. She was a 21-year-old nursing student. She died in a crash in a 2007 Chevrolet Cobalt while on her way to see her boyfriend. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe never really had a lot of information on what happened,â Ms. Raybuck said. The family never contacted G.M. They did not suspect a defect in the car until they heard of the recall years later, long after the vehicle had been scrapped for parts. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âAll of this has started coming back up, and we wonder what happened to her,&#8221; she said. &#8220;She was always so responsible. And she had a key chain with a lot on it, all her badges and nursing stuff.â </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The ignition switch defect is particularly sensitive to a heavy key chain.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ms. Raybuck said she felt the hearings were repetitive. âThey keep saying the same things.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI feel so bad for everybody affected,â she said. âIf people had known about the recall, known about the problems, they wouldnât have let their kids buy that car.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">She and her husband had helped Kelley select her Cobalt. âIf we had known, we wouldnât have let Kelley buy that car. They failed to let people know what was happening. People wouldnât have purchased those vehicles for their kids.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; <em>REBECCA R. RUIZ</em></p>
</div></div>
<div class="type-live-update update">
<div id="senator-mccaskill-accuses-g-m-officials-of-cover-up" class="updated-entry">
<h5 class="updated-marker highlight"><span class="time"><a href="#senator-mccaskill-accuses-g-m-officials-of-cover-up">11:00 A.M.</a></span> <strong>Senator McCaskill Accuses G.M. Officials of Cover-Up</strong></h5>
</p></div>
